Dear All,

Hope everyone is well.

As you may know, Marcia Horowitz, a veteran of Rubenstein Associates for ov=
er 41 years, passed away last year.  I am her husband.

During Marcia's 160-day bout with stage 4 pancreatic cancer, doctors and nu=
rses regularly told us that the approach we took in managing Marcia's illne=
ss was more uplifting than the norm.  The approach was in large part direct=
ed by Marcia, who, like for clients, found the calm within her own storm. S=
he opted for clarity and openness, not wanting to see her life as a tragedy=
 or be defined by cancer. This approach enabled us to make the most of Marc=
ia's remaining time, and not be swept into negative spirals.

After Marcia passed on February 10, 2020, doctors, nurses and others encour=
aged me to write a book about the experience.  It's called The Smooth River=
: Finding Inspiration and Exquisite Beauty during Terminal Illness. Lessons=
 from the Front Line<https://www.smoothriver.org/>.

The book is not a memoir or a how-to book in the traditional sense.  The on=
ly purpose is to help other people, using our experience as a case study to=
 derive some vital lessons in dealing with terminal disease or other tumult=
uous event, medical or other.  So far, the book has received some very good=
 reviews.  See https://www.smoothriver.org/reviews.

The book will be released on October 26, 2021, November being Pancreatic Ca=
ncer Awareness Month.  Pre-order information is available by:


